      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why P-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>P's 3-point face value gives it a natural scoring advantage over common 1-point tiles. With only two P tiles in the bag, you won't be overwhelmed by them, but when one arrives on your rack, it opens up strong plays. P pairs exceptionally with H (PH words like PHIZ, PHLOX, PHO), with R (PR- prefix words), and with X and Z for maximum damage.</p>
      <p>The PH combination is particularly powerful because it behaves like an F sound, giving you access to a whole family of words — PHONE, PHRASE, PHLEGM — while carrying P's 3 points plus H's 4 points as a base. That's 7 points from just two tiles before you even finish the word.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing P-Words</h2>
      <p>P rewards players who think about prefixes and letter combinations. Here are the key strategies for maximising your P-word scoring:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use P+X combinations:</strong> PAX, POX, PIX all score 12 points for three letters. On a triple-letter square under X, these become devastating compact plays.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Exploit the PH digraph:</strong> PH words give you flexibility when you have both P and H. PHIZ (18 pts) is a tournament favourite for tight board positions.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Build with PRE- prefix:</strong> PREFIX, PREXY, PRETZELS — the PRE- family offers long words that can hit multiple premium squares across the board.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Pizza and puzzle family:</strong> If you draw both P and Z together, you're in scoring paradise. PIZZA (25), PUZZLE (26), PIAZZA (26) are all massive plays.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Parallel play potential:</strong> P forms valid two-letter words (PA, PE, PI, PO) that enable parallel placement next to existing words for multi-word scoring turns.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Two-Letter P-Words to Memorise</h2>
      <p>These short P-words are essential for tight-board play and parallel scoring opportunities:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>PA, PE, PI, PO</strong> — all valid two-letter P-words in tournament play</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>PI</strong> (4 pts) is the most commonly played, enabling parallel placement alongside I-ending words</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Know all four</strong> — they unlock dozens of parallel play opportunities when the board gets crowded</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When to Hold vs Play Your P</h2>
      <p>P is a tile worth keeping for the right moment. If you have P alongside X or Z, prioritise finding a P+X or P+Z word over playing P in a lower-scoring combination. The synergy between P and high-value tiles often justifies holding P for one extra turn.</p>
      <p>However, don't hold P at the expense of rack balance. If P is your only consonant among five vowels, play it immediately to rebalance. A balanced rack always outperforms a lopsided one waiting for a dream combination that may never arrive.</p>

